article.description: Monique Currie scored 14 points to lift Duke (No. 4 ESPN/USA Today, No. 3 AP) past No. 24 Florida State 75-64.
article.headline: Devils' Currie plays with stress fractures in foot
article.linkText: Duke wins record 31st straight ACC home game
article.story:
DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- In recent weeks, Monique Currie practically carried Duke in its Atlantic Coast Conference games.

On Sunday, the Blue Devils gave their hurting star plenty of help.

Currie scored 14 points and was one of our players in double figures to lift Duke (No. 4 ESPN/USA Today, No. 3 AP) past No. 24 Florida State 75-64, setting a league record for consecutive home wins in Atlantic Coast Conference play.

Jessica Foley scored 11 points for the Blue Devils (22-2, 8-1 ACC), while freshmen Wanisha Smith and Laura Kurz also added 11 to help Duke earn its 31st straight home league win. That broke the record of 30 set by Virginia from 1992-96.

Kurz's production led a strong effort from Duke's bench, which outscored its counterpart 21-0 despite having just eight scholarship players.

"We need that to be successful," Duke coach Gail Goestenkors said. "It's a long season. All the teams are really focused on Monique. Anytime she puts the ball on the floor, they're double-teaming her. So we need some players to step up, and I think we're getting that."

That effort was particularly needed Sunday. Currie learned this weekend that she has stress fractures in her left foot, an injury that will likely require Goestenkors to ease the burden on the team's leading scorer.

Currie, who averages 18 points and eight rebounds a game, has been the main reason the Blue Devils have continued to thrive despite the departures of Alana Beard and Iciss Tillis.

Two weeks ago, Currie scored 22 of her 24 points in the second half of a 56-51 loss at North Carolina. Currie followed that by scoring 18 of her 24 points in the second half -- including the go-ahead jumper with 41.2 seconds left -- in a 60-57 win against Maryland.

Last week, she had 18 points and the go-ahead three-point play with 38 seconds left in a 52-49 win against North Carolina State.

But after going 5-for-14 against the Seminoles (19-5, 5-4), she will have time to rest before the Blue Devils travel to Maryland next weekend.

"It was a little uncomfortable," Currie said of her foot. "I can't run like I normally run, but it was relatively fine."

The Seminoles were the last ACC team to win at Cameron Indoor Stadium, taking a 71-69 win in February 2001. Florida State also ended Duke's record 51-game winning streak against league opponents last year in Tallahassee, Fla.

But the Blue Devils avoided any similar disappointment, using a 24-2 run early in the second half to erase a 37-34 deficit. Duke upped its defensive pressure, holding the Seminoles to one field goal over nine minutes and forcing turnovers that led to scores.

Smith scored eight points during the run, which ended with Kurz nailing a 3-pointer and hitting a layup for a 58-39 lead with 10:35 left.

In the run, Florida State went 1-for-13 from the floor with six turnovers, and Duke followed four of those miscues with baskets.

After allowing Florida State to shoot 52 percent in the first half, Duke's defense held the Seminoles to 10-for-28 shooting after the break. Most of that damage came with the Blue Devils playing a zone defense.

"We didn't attack it," FSU coach Sue Semrau said. "I was surprised, because we were doing such a great job attacking in the first half. I don't know if we just didn't get the looks we wanted or if we didn't hunt hard enough."

Ganiyat Adeduntan scored 19 points to lead the Seminoles, who have lost 23 of 25 meetings. Roneeka Hodges added 18 points.
